name: tris(3-methoxyphenyl)phosphine
Reason: 3-methoxyphenyl groups, when connected to a phosphine base, increase the melting point due to the enhancement of the crystalline structure and the increase in molecular weight. Each methoxy group introduces additional rigidity and hydrogen bonding potential, estimated at approximately +5 degrees Celsius. The phosphine base itself also contributes to the melting point due to its rigidity and potential for hydrogen bonding, estimated at approximately +20 degrees Celsius. The presence of three methoxyphenyl groups linked in a linear fashion raises the melting point due to increased pi-pi interactions and rigidity, estimated at approximately +60 degrees Celsius.
